</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B93E6C28B6075A60740F237FFD7DD28E" bold="true" box="[587,644,1913,1937]" pageId="2" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A20DD153B6075A60740F237FFD7DD28E" box="[587,644,1913,1937]" pageId="2" pageNumber="181" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, adult male. A, tergite IX and dorsal aspect of left gonocoxite and gonostylus. B, hypopygium with tergite IX removed, left dorsal aspect, right ventral aspect.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BF5B03AB6065A617683249FFB45D5E4" blockId="3.[151,1437,153,827]" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis id="B93E6C28B6065A617683249FFEFDD5AC" box="[199,260,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Head</emphasis>
. Eyes bare, frontal tubercles absent. AR 1.87 (1); ultimate flagellomere 732 (1) μm long. Temporal setae 17 (1). Clypeus with 23–25 setae. Tentorium 98–113 μm long, 29–49 μm wide. Palpomere lengths (in μm): 39–44, 34–39, 123–137, 113–118, 206 (1). Third palpal segment 3 sensilla clavata, longest 15–17 μm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF5B03AB6065A6176832500FCEFD45C" blockId="3.[151,1437,153,827]" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis id="B93E6C28B6065A6176832500FEF8D400" box="[199,257,262,287]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Wing</emphasis>
. VR 1.22–1.27. Brachiolum with 1 seta. R with 11–25 setae; R 
<subScript id="17CEB27FB6065A6175F22510FC47D43B" attach="left" box="[950,958,278,292]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">1</subScript>
with 13–17, R 
<subScript id="17CEB27FB6065A6172252510FB83D43B" attach="left" box="[1121,1146,278,292]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">4+5</subScript>
with 24–36 setae, remaining veins bare. Squama with 8–11 setae. Anal lobe weak.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF5B03AB6065A617683254BFEBCD494" blockId="3.[151,1437,153,827]" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis id="B93E6C28B6065A617683254BFEE1D478" box="[199,280,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Thorax</emphasis>
. Scutum with low tubercle. Dorsocentrals 13–20; acrostichals 10–12; prealars 5. Scutellum with 12–16 setae, uniserial.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF5B03AB6065A6176832590FA7DD4E8" blockId="3.[151,1437,153,827]" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis id="B93E6C28B6065A6176832590FF05D4B0" box="[199,252,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Legs</emphasis>
. Scale of foretibia 29–34 μm long, rounded and without spur. Spur of midtibia 54–59 μm long, including 49–54 μm long comb. Spur of hind tibia 64–83 μm long, including 49–64 μm long comb. Width at apex of foretibia 44–49 μm, of midtibia 49–54 μm, of hind tibia 49–59 μm. Lengths (in μm) and proportions of legs as in 
<tableCitation id="C6C88581B6065A61736E25DBFA79D4E8" box="[1322,1408,477,503]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,239,874,898]" captionText="TABLE 2. Lengths (in μm) and proportions of leg segments in Polypedilum (Asheum) sofiae Pinho &amp; Silva, sp. n., adult male (n = 1–2)." pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Table 2</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF5B03AB6065A6176832604FEC7D7D0" blockId="3.[151,1437,153,827]" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis id="B93E6C28B6065A6176832604FEAFD704" box="[199,342,514,539]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Hypopygium</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="1371ACBFB6065A6177212607FE05D704" box="[357,508,513,539]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1912,1937]" captionTargetBox="[153,1388,752,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,741,1886]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Polypedilum (Asheum) sofiae sp. n., adult male. A, tergite IX and dorsal aspect of left gonocoxite and gonostylus. B, hypopygium with tergite IX removed, left dorsal aspect, right ventral aspect." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3737395" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3737395/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Figure 1A, B</figureCitation>
). Tergite IX with 7–10 median setae. Anal tergite band well developed. Laterosternite with 3–4 setae. Anal point 35–42 μm long, slender. Phallapodeme 92–102 μm long, transverse sternapodeme 20–30 μm long. Gonocoxite 169–199 μm long. Superior volsella pediform with apical outer margin convex, 77–80 μm long, basal 2/3 covered with microtrichia and with 4 inner setae. Inferior volsella slender 97–100 μm long, with 1 strong apical seta projecting caudad, and 12–14 orally directed setae. Gonostylus 92–115 μm long. HR 1.74–1.83; HV 2.76–3.18.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF5B03AB6065A61768326DFFDA1D7EC" blockId="3.[151,1437,153,827]" box="[199,600,729,755]" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis id="B93E6C28B6065A61768326DFFE25D7EC" box="[199,476,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Female, pupa and larva.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C350E3B1B6065A61768326FAFDD7D624" pageId="3" pageNumber="182" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BF5B03AB6065A61768326FAFDD7D624" blockId="3.[151,1437,153,827]" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis id="B93E6C28B6065A61768326FAFE98D608" bold="true" box="[199,353,764,791]" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Distribution.</emphasis>
The new species is known from two localities in Brazilian Amazon and Cerrado in the states of 
<collectingRegion id="498E7ED8B6065A6176D32727FEFDD624" box="[151,260,801,827]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="498E7ED8B6065A61777F2727FE35D624" box="[315,460,801,827]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="1371ACBFB6065A61779F2727FDD9D624" box="[475,544,800,827]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1999,2024]" captionTargetBox="[179,1409,849,1975]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[179,1409,849,1975]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distribution of Polypedilum (Asheum) in neotropical region." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3737403" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3737403/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="182">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
